We say, Thirdly, that even if the Law be not only made with an evil intention, but be in some measure a mischievous law, still the subject is bound to obey the law, when made by due authority, provided the matter of the law, the thing commanded, be such as can be done without sin. The Reason is this: that each person ought to take especial care of that which belongs to his own business3 and not to be too anxious and scrupulous in matters which are the business of others. “Every man shall bear his own burthen,” Gal. vi. 5. If the Legislator is wanting in his duty, what is that to thee? Take that thine is, and go thy way. As to his intention, whether it is right or otherwise, let him look to that3 he will have to render an account to his Lord, of his actions and of his intentions too. And thou, if thou obey not, wilt have to render to the same Lord an account of thy disobedience.
